= AGENTS

This file provides instructions for AI agents working on this codebase.

== Python Version

- Use Python 3.13 for Apple Silicon (M1/M2/M3) Macs
- Create venv as `.venv313`
- Python 3.14 is incompatible with PyTorch 2.8.0 (SIGSEGV with libomp)

== Documentation

- Use AsciiDoc (.asc) format, NOT Markdown (.md)
- Files: README.asc, CONTRIBUTING.asc, SECURITY.asc, TRANSLATING.asc, CLI_POLICY.asc

== Running Tests

----
pip install -r requirements-dev.txt

venv/bin/python -m pytest -q
----

== CLI Usage

----
rag --query "your question"
rag-tui
rag-agent  # Minimal app-style TUI
----

=== rag-agent

The `rag-agent` command launches the minimal app-style TUI:

----
bin/rag-agent          # Direct execution
rag-agent              # After pip install -e .
----

This is an entry point (not a symlink) that wraps `src/rag/ui/minimal_tui.py`.

=== Model Switching

`rag`, `rag-tui`, and `rag-agent` all support:

----
models
model: <name>
----

In `rag-tui`, you can also type `model` to pick from a list (no need to type the full model name).

=== Environment Keys (.env)

The app auto-loads a repo-root `.env` file (gitignored). A starter template exists at `.env.example`.

Common settings:

----
RAG_LLM_BACKEND=openai|cerebras|ollama|local
OPENAI_API_KEY=...
OPENAI_MODEL=gpt-5.3-chat-latest
CEREBRAS_API_KEY=...
CEREBRAS_MODEL=llama3.1-8b
OLLAMA_MODEL=llama3
----

== Setting Up on a New Computer

When starting work on a fresh machine, follow these steps to set up the RAG environment.

NOTE: The setup script automatically uses the system's default Python version. For Apple Silicon Macs, ensure Python 3.13 is installed and available as `python3`.

=== Automated Setup (Recommended)

----
# 1. Clone the repository
git clone <repo-url> && cd rag

# 2. Run the setup script
bash SETUP.sh

# 3. Open a new terminal or run:
source ~/.zshrc  # or ~/.bashrc if using bash

# 4. Test the installation
rag --help
----

=== Manual Setup

If you prefer manual control:

----
# 1. Create virtual environment
python3 -m venv venv

# 2. Activate the virtual environment
source venv/bin/activate

# 3. Install dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt

# 4. Install RAG in editable mode
pip install -e .

# 5. Add to your shell's PATH
echo 'export PATH="/path/to/rag/venv/bin:$PATH"' >> ~/.zshrc
source ~/.zshrc

# 6. Test it
rag --help
----

=== Verification

After setup, verify the installation works:

----
rag --version
rag --query "What is machine learning?"
rag-agent --help
rag-tui --help
----

=== Files Created During Setup

- `venv/` - Virtual environment directory
- Shell config updated (`.zshrc` or `.bashrc`) - Adds venv bin to PATH

== Key Files

- `SETUP.sh` - Automated setup script for new computers
- `setup_rag.sh` - Comprehensive setup script with optional sudo wrappers
- `setup-apple-silicon.sh` - Apple Silicon setup script
- `.github/workflows/apple-silicon-setup.yml` - CI workflow for Apple Silicon
- `scripts/test_release.sh` - Test release workflow locally (dry-run)
- `scripts/local_release.sh` - Run full release locally

== Commit Message Convention

IMPORTANT: When making code changes, use the correct commit type so semantic-release can automatically publish releases.

This project uses https://www.conventionalcommits.org/[Conventional Commits] for automated releases via semantic-release.

|===
| Type | Description | Release

| `feat` | New feature | minor bump
| `fix` | Bug fix | patch bump
| `perf` | Performance improvement | patch bump
| `refactor` | Code refactoring | patch bump
| `docs` | Documentation only | no release
| `chore` | Maintenance tasks | no release
| `test` | Adding/updating tests | no release
| `ci` | CI configuration changes | no release
|===

Breaking changes (add `!` before `:`): `feat!:` or `fix!:` → major bump

Examples:

----
feat: add new search filter
fix: resolve memory leak in cache
feat!: change API response format
docs: update installation instructions
chore: update dependencies
----

== GitHub Discussions (GraphQL API)

When `gh discussion` command is not available, use the GitHub GraphQL API:

=== Create a Discussion

[source,bash]
----
# 1. Get repository ID
gh api graphql -f query='query { repository(owner: "bniladridas", name: "rag") { id } }' --jq '.data.repository.id'

# 2. Get discussion categories
gh api graphql -f query='query { repository(owner: "bniladridas", name: "rag") { discussionCategories(first: 10) { nodes { id name } } } }'

# 3. Create discussion (example: General category)
gh api graphql -f query='mutation($repositoryId:ID!, $categoryId:ID!, $title:String!, $body:String!){createDiscussion(input:{repositoryId:$repositoryId, categoryId:$categoryId, title:$title, body:$body}){discussion{id url}}}' \
  -f repositoryId="R_kgDON015pw" \
  -f categoryId="DIC_kwDON015p84C5BiF" \
  -f title="Your Title" \
  -f body="Your content in Markdown"
----

=== Available Categories

|===
| Category | ID Suffix

| Announcements | 84C5BiE
| General | 84C5BiF
| Ideas | 84C5BiH
| Q&A | 84C5BiG
| Show and tell | 84C5BiI
| Polls | 84C5BiJ
|===

=== Useful Queries

[source,bash]
----
# List all discussions
gh api graphql -f query='query { repository(owner: "bniladridas", name: "rag") { discussions(first: 10) { nodes { title url number } } } }'

# Get single discussion
gh api graphql -f query='query { discussion(number: 76) { title body url } }'
----

== Understanding This Codebase

=== Python & Ollama Integration

- Backend options: `openai`, `cerebras`, `ollama`, `local`
- Set via `.env` or runtime: `model: <name>`
- Local models require Ollama running: `ollama serve`

=== Repository Structure

----
rag/
├── src/rag/           # Core engine, tools, UI
├── scripts/           # Release, setup, lint scripts
├── .github/workflows/ # CI/CD pipelines
├── docs/              # Additional documentation
└── release-webpage/   # GitHub Pages site
----

=== Finding Bugs & Issues

1. Check https://github.com/bniladridas/rag/issues[Issues] for reported bugs
2. Check https://github.com/bniladridas/rag/discussions[Discussions] for questions
3. Run tests: `pytest -q`
4. Check CI status in Actions tab
- `SETUP_GUIDE.asc` - Setup entrypoint alias for `AGENTS.asc`
